1-----Method Overloading (Compile-Time Polymorphism)

1. What is Method Overloading?

Definition
Method Overloading means having multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists in the same class.

Interview Definition
Method Overloading is the process of defining multiple methods with the same name but different parameters in the same class.

Why Do We Need Method Overloading?
Suppose you are creating a Calculator.
Without overloading
class Calculator {

    int add2Numbers(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    int add3Numbers(int a, int b, int c) {
        return a + b + c;
    }

    double addDouble(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }
}

Problems:

Different method names
Difficult to remember
Poor readability
Solution: Method Overloading

class Calculator {

    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    int add(int a, int b, int c) {
        return a + b + c;
    }

    double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }
}

Now all methods have one meaningful name:

add()
Java automatically chooses the correct one.

2. How Does Java Decide Which Method to Call?

Example

class Calculator {

    void add(int a, int b) {
        System.out.println("Two Integers");
    }

    void add(double a, double b) {
        System.out.println("Two Doubles");
    }
}
Calculator c = new Calculator();

c.add(10,20);

c.add(10.5,20.5);

Output

Two Integers
Two Doubles
Why?

The compiler checks the arguments and selects the correct method.

This is called Compile-Time Polymorphism.

3. Rules of Method Overloading

A method is overloaded if it differs by parameters.
There are three valid ways:


Rule 1: Different Number of Parameters

void add(int a,int b)

void add(int a,int b,int c)

Valid ✅


Rule 2: Different Type of Parameters
void add(int a,int b)

void add(double a,double b)

Valid ✅


Rule 3: Different Order of Parameters
void display(int age,String name)

void display(String name,int age)

Valid ✅


4. What is NOT Method Overloading?
Only Changing Return Type
int add(int a,int b){

}

double add(int a,int b){

}

❌ Compile Error

Why?

When calling

add(10,20);

Java doesn't look at the return type.

It only looks at:

Method name
Parameters
  Method Signature

