This becomes Overloading, not Overriding.

Rule 3
Same Return Type (or Covariant Return Type)
int show()
↓
int show()
✔ Correct

4. @Override Annotation
Example
class Animal {
    void sound() {
    }

}
class Dog extends Animal {

    @Override
    void sound() {

    }

}
Why use @Override?

It tells the compiler:

"I intend to override this method."

If you accidentally make a mistake:

@Override
void sounds() {

}

Compile Error.

Without @Override, Java would treat sounds() as a new method, and you might not notice the mistake.


5. Can We Override static Methods?
class Animal {

    static void show() {

    }

}

class Dog extends Animal {

    static void show() {

    }

}

This is not overriding.

It is Method Hiding.

Why?

Static methods belong to the class, not to objects.

Runtime polymorphism works with objects.

6. Can We Override final Methods?
class Animal {

    final void sound() {

    }

}

class Dog extends Animal {

    void sound() {

    }

}

Compile Error.

Why?

final means

Cannot Be Changed

So the child cannot override it.

7. Can We Override private Methods?
class Animal {

    private void show() {

    }

}

class Dog extends Animal {

    void show() {

    }

}

This is not overriding.

Why?

Because private methods are not inherited.

The show() in Dog is a completely new method.

