Why Does C++ Need virtual?

C++ is designed for performance and programmer control.

If every function were virtual by default:

More memory would be needed (vtable pointers).
Method calls would be slightly slower.
Programs that don't need polymorphism would pay that cost.

So C++ lets the programmer choose.

Why Doesn't Java Need virtual?

Java was designed for simplicity and safety.

By default, every instance method (except static, final, and private) behaves like a virtual function.

So Java automatically supports runtime polymorphism.
